  "questions": [
    {
      "text": "A 13-year-old boy is brought to the physician by his father for evaluation prior to participation in sports. He feels well. He has no history of serious illness and takes no medications. He is at the 60th percentile for height and 80th percentile for weight. His vital signs are within normal limits. Cardiopulmonary examination shows no abnormalities. When the patient is standing, examination of the feet shows depressed medial longitudinal arches, heel eversion, and forefoot abduction bilaterally. The medial longitudinal arches are restored when the great toes are dorsiflexed, and when the patient is examined in the prone position. Strength is 5/5 in both lower extremities. Active and passive ranges of motion of the lower extremities are full. Which of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?",
      "choices": [
        {
          "id": 1,
          "text": "Weight-bearing x-rays of both feet"
        },
        {
          "id": 2,
          "text": "Orthotic use"
        },
        {
          "id": 3,
          "text": "Reassurance"
        },
        {
          "id": 4,
          "text": "Achilles tendon lengthening"
        },
        {
          "id": 5,
          "text": "MRI of the spine"
        }
      ],
      "correct_choice_id": 3,
      "solution": "<div><h4 style='color: #f87171; font-weight: bold; margin-top: 16px; font-size: 1.125rem;'>A) INCORRECT:</h4>\n<span data-sememe-id=\"NTV-IF0\">Weight-bearing</span> <a href=\"https://www.amboss.com/us/library#xid=in0JGg&anker=Zf22a2d04575027ccbd9bc2a111f58066\" data-learningcard-id=\"in0JGg\" data-anker=\"Zf22a2d04575027ccbd9bc2a111f58066\" data-sememe-id=\"eK0x2S\">x-rays</a> of the feet are indicated in patients with <a href=\"https://www.amboss.com/us/library#xid=4G03zh&anker=Zbfe606ff082be04c3477402a5931edf1\" data-learningcard-id=\"4G03zh\" data-anker=\"Zbfe606ff082be04c3477402a5931edf1\" data-section-id=\"rjWfbl0\" data-sememe-id=\"CdWqH40\">flexible flat feet</a> who present with <a href=\"https://www.amboss.com/us/library#xid=xN0EWg&anker=Zd673a3f7ee36023aab5a267899e984cc\" data-learningcard-id=\"xN0EWg\" data-anker=\"Zd673a3f7ee36023aab5a267899e984cc\" data-section-id=\"NBX-a00\">pain</a>, decreased <a href=\"https://www.amboss.com/us/library#xid=zl0rzT&anker=Z39ea92ae5426bd72cbb3aaf20a6c5846\" data-learningcard-id=\"zl0rzT\" data-anker=\"Z39ea92ae5426bd72cbb3aaf20a6c5846\" data-section-id=\"hxXcwZ0\" data-sememe-id=\"Se1yyf0\">range of motion</a>, or require <a href=\"https://www.amboss.com/us/library#xid=aj0Q_f&anker=Zd56b596870b749fc123f8c0d759753ba\" data-learningcard-id=\"aj0Q_f\" data-anker=\"Zd56b596870b749fc123f8c0d759753ba\" data-section-id=\"IYWYqP0\">preoperative evaluation</a>. This patient is asymptomatic and has full active and passive ranges of motion in the lower extremities, so he does not require <span data-sememe-id=\"NTV-IF0\">weight-bearing</span> <a href=\"https://www.amboss.com/us/library#xid=in0JGg&anker=Zf22a2d04575027ccbd9bc2a111f58066\" data-learningcard-id=\"in0JGg\" data-anker=\"Zf22a2d04575027ccbd9bc2a111f58066\" data-sememe-id=\"eK0x2S\">x-rays</a> of the feet.</div><div><h4 style='color: #f87171; font-weight: bold; margin-top: 16px; font-size: 1.125rem;'>B) INCORRECT:</h4>\n<span data-sememe-id=\"wXahZj\">Orthotic insoles</span> are not recommended for children with asymptomatic <a href=\"https://www.amboss.com/us/library#xid=4G03zh&anker=Zbfe606ff082be04c3477402a5931edf1\" data-learningcard-id=\"4G03zh\" data-anker=\"Zbfe606ff082be04c3477402a5931edf1\" data-section-id=\"rjWfbl0\" data-sememe-id=\"CdWqH40\">functional flat feet</a> because there is insufficient evidence that this treatment improves <span data-sememe-id=\"MfWM5k0\">clinical outcomes</span>.</div><div><h4 style='color: #34d399; font-weight: bold; margin-top: 16px; font-size: 1.125rem;'>C) CORRECT:</h4>Most cases of <a href=\"https://www.amboss.com/us/library#xid=4G03zh&anker=Zbfe606ff082be04c3477402a5931edf1\" data-learningcard-id=\"4G03zh\" data-anker=\"Zbfe606ff082be04c3477402a5931edf1\" data-section-id=\"rjWfbl0\" data-sememe-id=\"CdWqH40\">functional flat feet</a> in children are <span class=\"wichtig\"><b>physiologic</b></span> and often <span class=\"wichtig\"><b>resolve spontaneously</b></span> during <span data-sememe-id=\"sT1tHT0\">adolescence</span>. Therefore, <span class=\"wichtig\"><b>reassurance </b></span>and <span class=\"wichtig\"><b><span data-sememe-id=\"2ycTeU0\">expectant management</span></b></span> are recommended for asymptomatic individuals. If the deformity is associated with <a href=\"https://www.amboss.com/us/library#xid=xN0EWg&anker=Zd673a3f7ee36023aab5a267899e984cc\" data-learningcard-id=\"xN0EWg\" data-anker=\"Zd673a3f7ee36023aab5a267899e984cc\" data-section-id=\"NBX-a00\">pain</a> and/or limited <a href=\"https://www.amboss.com/us/library#xid=zl0rzT&anker=Z39ea92ae5426bd72cbb3aaf20a6c5846\" data-learningcard-id=\"zl0rzT\" data-anker=\"Z39ea92ae5426bd72cbb3aaf20a6c5846\" data-section-id=\"hxXcwZ0\" data-sememe-id=\"Se1yyf0\">range of motion</a>, further diagnostic (e.g., <span data-sememe-id=\"NTV-IF0\">weight-bearing</span> <a href=\"https://www.amboss.com/us/library#xid=in0JGg&anker=Zf22a2d04575027ccbd9bc2a111f58066\" data-learningcard-id=\"in0JGg\" data-anker=\"Zf22a2d04575027ccbd9bc2a111f58066\" data-sememe-id=\"eK0x2S\">x-rays</a> of the feet) and treatment are indicated. <span data-sememe-id=\"cdbaKs\">Conservative treatment</span> of painful <a href=\"https://www.amboss.com/us/library#xid=4G03zh&anker=Z01ea640b4fb9d321bd3e51cea15d69a8\" data-learningcard-id=\"4G03zh\" data-anker=\"Z01ea640b4fb9d321bd3e51cea15d69a8\" data-sememe-id=\"pC1LGQ0\">flat feet</a> involves <span data-sememe-id=\"FZXgW9\">physical therapy</span> and adequate shoe wear (e.g., orthotic use, supported heel counter). <a href=\"https://www.amboss.com/us/library#xid=4G03zh&anker=Zbfe606ff082be04c3477402a5931edf1\" data-learningcard-id=\"4G03zh\" data-anker=\"Zbfe606ff082be04c3477402a5931edf1\" data-section-id=\"rjWfbl0\" data-sememe-id=\"CdWqH40\">Flexible flat feet</a> associated with limited ranges of motion can be caused by <a href=\"https://www.amboss.com/us/library#xid=p60LNS&anker=Zba7c7a625919481ddcf9acc729603073\" data-learningcard-id=\"p60LNS\" data-anker=\"Zba7c7a625919481ddcf9acc729603073\" data-section-id=\"bvcHAV0\" data-sememe-id=\"vUcAUb0\">Achilles tendon</a> <a href=\"https://www.amboss.com/us/library#xid=hQ0cDf&anker=Zd2a2f37a9ccc074254e9331a5ba6126c\" data-learningcard-id=\"hQ0cDf\" data-anker=\"Zd2a2f37a9ccc074254e9331a5ba6126c\" data-section-id=\"u4cpOc0\" data-sememe-id=\"0Q0euf\">contractures</a>, which may require surgical treatment.</div><div><h4 style='color: #f87171; font-weight: bold; margin-top: 16px; font-size: 1.125rem;'>D) INCORRECT:</h4>\n<a href=\"https://www.amboss.com/us/library#xid=p60LNS&anker=Zba7c7a625919481ddcf9acc729603073\" data-learningcard-id=\"p60LNS\" data-anker=\"Zba7c7a625919481ddcf9acc729603073\" data-section-id=\"bvcHAV0\" data-sememe-id=\"vUcAUb0\">Achilles tendon</a> lengthening, which can be achieved by passive stretching or surgical reconstruction, is indicated in cases of <a href=\"https://www.amboss.com/us/library#xid=4G03zh&anker=Z01ea640b4fb9d321bd3e51cea15d69a8\" data-learningcard-id=\"4G03zh\" data-anker=\"Z01ea640b4fb9d321bd3e51cea15d69a8\" data-sememe-id=\"pC1LGQ0\">flat feet</a> that are associated with <a href=\"https://www.amboss.com/us/library#xid=hQ0cDf&anker=Zd2a2f37a9ccc074254e9331a5ba6126c\" data-learningcard-id=\"hQ0cDf\" data-anker=\"Zd2a2f37a9ccc074254e9331a5ba6126c\" data-section-id=\"u4cpOc0\" data-sememe-id=\"0Q0euf\">contractures</a> of the <a href=\"https://www.amboss.com/us/library#xid=p60LNS&anker=Z87ff0463168218333b6dfb92301686c0\" data-learningcard-id=\"p60LNS\" data-anker=\"Z87ff0463168218333b6dfb92301686c0\" data-section-id=\"bvcHAV0\" data-sememe-id=\"8tYO2I\">triceps surae muscle</a> that lead to limited ranges of motion. There is no evidence of muscle <a href=\"https://www.amboss.com/us/library#xid=hQ0cDf&anker=Zd2a2f37a9ccc074254e9331a5ba6126c\" data-learningcard-id=\"hQ0cDf\" data-anker=\"Zd2a2f37a9ccc074254e9331a5ba6126c\" data-section-id=\"u4cpOc0\" data-sememe-id=\"0Q0euf\">contractures</a> in this patient, and the <a href=\"https://www.amboss.com/us/library#xid=zl0rzT&anker=Z39ea92ae5426bd72cbb3aaf20a6c5846\" data-learningcard-id=\"zl0rzT\" data-anker=\"Z39ea92ae5426bd72cbb3aaf20a6c5846\" data-section-id=\"hxXcwZ0\" data-sememe-id=\"Se1yyf0\">range of motion</a> in his feet is normal, so a different step in management is more appropriate.</div><div><h4 style='color: #f87171; font-weight: bold; margin-top: 16px; font-size: 1.125rem;'>E) INCORRECT:</h4>In patients with <a href=\"https://www.amboss.com/us/library#xid=4G03zh&anker=Z01ea640b4fb9d321bd3e51cea15d69a8\" data-learningcard-id=\"4G03zh\" data-anker=\"Z01ea640b4fb9d321bd3e51cea15d69a8\" data-sememe-id=\"pC1LGQ0\">flat feet</a>, an <a href=\"https://www.amboss.com/us/library#xid=pN0LXg&anker=Zefb6206a3f821bf7e5942b654dc6f6cf\" data-learningcard-id=\"pN0LXg\" data-anker=\"Zefb6206a3f821bf7e5942b654dc6f6cf\" data-sememe-id=\"8n0OEg\">MRI</a> of the <a href=\"https://www.amboss.com/us/library#xid=E6085S&anker=Z46dd80e8ba8f4ec5caa956e468a8c384\" data-learningcard-id=\"E6085S\" data-anker=\"Z46dd80e8ba8f4ec5caa956e468a8c384\">spine</a> is indicated when a spinal cause is suspected. <a href=\"https://www.amboss.com/us/library#xid=el0xDT&anker=Z055c25fa28c4eb8c6bb0672e557eef80\" data-learningcard-id=\"el0xDT\" data-anker=\"Z055c25fa28c4eb8c6bb0672e557eef80\" data-sememe-id=\"fn0ksg\">Neural tube defects</a>, such as <a href=\"https://www.amboss.com/us/library#xid=el0xDT&anker=Zd3bbfdcf2f0e01746bbc2ac14e25ccb8\" data-learningcard-id=\"el0xDT\" data-anker=\"Zd3bbfdcf2f0e01746bbc2ac14e25ccb8\" data-section-id=\"2CXTrZ0\" data-sememe-id=\"GSaBa4\">meningomyelocele</a>, can lead to neuromuscular dysfunction and subsequent <a href=\"https://www.amboss.com/us/library#xid=qQ0CCf&anker=Zdcfc28c9aba3fda5547fd10d241c626e\" data-learningcard-id=\"qQ0CCf\" data-anker=\"Zdcfc28c9aba3fda5547fd10d241c626e\">foot deformities</a>. This patient has no other symptoms of spinal cord dysfunction (e.g., motor or sensory defects, <a href=\"https://www.amboss.com/us/library#xid=Rp0l6S&anker=Zb39fa0c160d5f2d2d45d0f06da0f4fcf\" data-learningcard-id=\"Rp0l6S\" data-anker=\"Zb39fa0c160d5f2d2d45d0f06da0f4fcf\" data-section-id=\"qwcCPe0\">bladder</a> or bowel dysfunction), so a spinal cause is unlikely.</div>",
      "hint": "This patient's depressed medial longitudinal arches (MLA) with heel eversion and forefoot abduction are indicative of flat foot (pes planus). The restoration of the MLA in prone position and the full range of motion suggests a functional (flexible) flat foot, which is common in children and adolescents.",
